[ProMED-mail thanks Remigio Russo for submitting the news report above.

Rozzano is a town in the Metropolitan City of Milan in the Italian region of Lombardy; Rozzano is located about 9 km (6 mi) south of Milan (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rozzano). A map showing the location of the school the 6-year-old attended on Via Garofani in Rozzano can be found at https://www.google.co.uk/maps/place/Via+Garofani,+20089+Rozzano+MI,+Italy. Bergamo, where the child died, is a city in Lombardy, northern Italy, about 40 km (25 mi) northeast of Milan (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bergamo).

Although the news report does not mention the microbial etiology of the meningitis that killed the 6-year-old, it was likely _Neisseria meningitidis_, for which antibiotic chemoprophylaxis is given to close contacts.

In Italy, as of January 2017, meningococcus serogroup B vaccine is to be given to children under one year of age and meningococcal serogroup C conjugate vaccine is to be given to children between 13-15 months of age; quadrivalent meningococcus serogroups ACWY conjugate vaccine is to be given to adolescents, age 12-14 (http://vaccine-schedule.ecdc.europa.eu/Pages/Scheduler.aspx). The meningococcus vaccine status of the 6-year-old who died is not mentioned in the news report above. - Mod.ML]
